<p>&#8220;Is now the time to be a hero?&#8221;<span id="more-54090"></span></p>
<p>The Trump administration&#8217;s brazen interferences with academic freedom and university governance, its punishment of students for exercising their freedom of expression, its drastic cutting of research funding and financial aid, and its attempts to block international students from studying in the US, taken together, constitute an unprecedented attack on higher education.</p>
<p>What are you going to do about it? What should you do about it? What&#8217;s at stake is important, but speaking out or taking action in response to this attack, or to other moves and policies of the current government, may be dangerous. Heroes stand up for values even when doing so is risky. Is now the time for you to be hero? And what does heroism in this context look like?</p>
<p>In the following guest post, <a href="https://www.elizabethharman.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Elizabeth Harman</strong></a>, professor in the Department of Philosophy and Center for Human Values at Princeton University, takes up these and related questions.</p>
<p>This is the second post in the <a class="wp-dark-mode-bg-image" href="https://dailynous.com/tag/summer-guest-post-series-2025/">2025 Summer Guest Post Series</a>.</p>
<hr />
